Sense of Vision
The sense of vision or sight in man y animals is much superior than human beings. 
The member s of the cat family like the lion, cat and leopar d have exceptionally 
excellen t nigh t vision that help s them to hunt even in the dark. A tiger can see six 
times better than human beings at nigh t.Super Senses of AnimalsUnitâ€“II : The Living World
4
Just like human beings, animals also have sense organs that help them to hear , 
smell, taste, see and feel the world around them. It has been noticed that in 
animals, sense organs are sharper than humans. Their super senses help 
them to find their food, communicate with each other and protect 
themselv es from their enemies.Let'sKnow Let'sKnow
Environmental Studies-527

Birds of prey like eagle, vultur e, hawk etc. can see four times as far as humans can. 
An eagle can spot a mouse on the ground from high up in the sky.
Sense of Smell
Animals like cats, mice, rats, squirr els etc. have a good sense of smell. They use 
their sensitiv e whisk ers to sear ch for their food.
Dogs have a very strong sense of smell. Sniffer dogs are used by the police to trace 
criminals and to find things like bomb s, drugs etc. 
Shark s combine their keen sense of smell with the timing to determine the 
direction of smell. They follow the nostrils that first detect the smell and thus find 
their food.
Sense of Hearing
Man y animals use sounds in order to communic ate with one another . Animals like 
monk eys mak e ho wling sounds t o warn other s about an y dang er. Dogs bark, c ats 
purr, birds chirp and frogs croak to convey joy, dang er, fear, anger and the need to 
mate. Deer and other gr azing animals' sense of hearing pr ovide them w arning of 
the appr oaching predators. Fox and other hunting animals have well developed 
sense of hearing that help s them to locate their prey.
! Bats, whales and dolphins mak e a loud sound. The echo of the sound help s 
them to locate their food as well as avoid the obstacles on the way.An eagle can focus on the prey in front as well as on objects on either 
side of it without moving its head.You  Know Must (Knowledge )
! Crocodiles can hear their young ones insid e their eggs.
! A humpba ck whale comm unic ates with beeps and calls that sound like a 
song and can be hear d by other whales miles awa y.You  Know Must (Knowledge )
Sense of T ouch
! Cat's whisk ers and the stiffer hair along its body are great at feeling around. 
They can sense a chang e in the air currents very fast. This help s them feel 
their way around in the dark.

Sense of T aste
! A catfish is the greatest 'super taster'  in the world. 
Catfish have a unique taste recep tion system. They 
have taste recep tors not only in their mouth but 
their entire body is covered in them.
! Bees ha ve a s trong sense of t aste. The y have taste 
sensor s on their antennae and on their front feet. 
Some worker bees bring nect ar for the other bees to taste. If the bees like the 
taste, then they all go to collect the nect ar .
! A butterfly tastes the food with its feet as mos t of the taste buds are presen t 
on its feet.
! Cockr oaches, spider s and man y other insects have hair on their legs. The hair 
help them to feel out their surroundings. This sense of 
touch is also called tactile sense .
! Snak es can feel the smalles t vibrations in the ground 
with the help of a bone in their jaw. It is called the 
hearing bone.
! Shark s have well developed touch recep tors located in their skin, all over 
their body . They use these sensor s to feel water currents and temper ature 
chang es.
Do Animals Sleep?
Like human beings, animals also need sleep to refresh themselv es . Different 
animals have different ways of sleeping.
! Horses sleep while standing.
! Cows sleep with their eyes open.
! Bats hang themselv es upside down and sleep.
! A giraffe sleep s with one of its eyes open and both ears moving.
! Migr atory birds need to cover long distances, so they sleep while flying.
! Fish and snak es do not have eyelids, so they sleep with their eyes open.
! Whales and dolphins do not sleep comple tely. Their brains are half awake 
which enables them to keep on swimming in water and reminds them to 
come to the surface for breathing.

Group Behaviour in Animals
Some animals live together and move around in groups for various reasons such 
asâ€“
! They feel safe and protected in large groups.
! Mos t of the grazing animals like cows, sheep buffaloes, deer , zebras, horses 
etc. move in groups called herds for food, water and shelt er.
! Living in groups help s them to take care of their young ones in a better way.
! Social animals like hone ybees, termit es and ants live in large groups called 
colonies. They shar e their work in the group. Some get food for the group, the 
other s protect and look after the group.! Some animals like lizards escape unfavourable clima tic conditions such as 
severe cold by sleeping for long durations of time. This sleep-lik e state can 
last an entire season. This winter sleep is called hiberna tion. Animals like 
bear s, snak es, bees and bats hiberna te.
! Some animals like snails, earth worms, salamander , desert tortoise and 
crocodiles sleep through hot summer mon ths to escape the heat. This 
summer sleep is called aestivation.
! Some animals like owls, bats and rats are inactiv e during the day but are very 
activ e at nigh t. Such animals are called nocturnal animals .
Hone ybeesâ€“ Hone ybees live in beehiv es. Every beehiv e has on Queen Bee that lays 
eggs. Ther e are only a few males in the hive. Mos t of the bees in the hive are 
worker-bees. The worker-bees work all the day. They mak e the hive and also look 
after the baby bees. They collect nect ar from the flowers. Once their stomachs are 
full, they spit out the nect ar into the cells of their hives. After a few days, this nect ar 
turns into hone y. Without worker-bees there would be neither hive nor any nect ar 
collection.
Antsâ€“ Ants live and work together like hone y bees. The Queen Ant lays the eggs. 
The Soldier Ants look after and guar d the ants nest. The Worker Ants are always 
busy looking for food and bringing it to the nest. 
Termit es and wasps also live like this.Social Behaviour of Some Animals

Terrestrial Plants
Plan ts that grow in moun tain regionsâ€”  The 
weather in moun tains is normally very cold and 
windy . Snowfall also occur s in some areas. Trees 
that grow here have to survive in cold. Pine, 
spruce, cedar and fir are some plan ts that grow 
in moun tain regions.
Adaptation in Plants5
Different plan ts grow in different regions. The plan ts growing in a particular 
region develop some special features that help them adjust to their 
surroundings and survive.
The process of developing special features in the body to adjus t in the 
surroundings is called adap tation. Let's study about the special features of 
some  plan ts growing in different surroundings.
We can divide the plan ts in two categoriesâ€”
 1. Terrestrial plan ts â€” The plan ts that grow on land.  
 2. Aqua tic plan tsâ€” The plan ts that grow in water.(Knowledge )
Let'sKnow Let'sKnow
Environmental Studies-535Unitâ€“II : The Living World

Special featuresâ€”
! Trees are tall, thin and straigh t.
! They are cone shaped that help s the snow to slide off easily . Due to the 
conic al shape they are called conifers.
! They bear cones instead of flowers. Cones have seeds inside them.
! They have needle shaped leaves which have a waxy coating to prevent 
damag e from water.
Plan ts that grow in plainsâ€” Trees like banyan, neem, peepal, mang o etc. grow in 
the warmer clima te of the plains.
Special featuresâ€”
! They have man y branches that spread around.
! Their branches have man y flat and thin leaves which help in evapor ation of 
excess water and keeping them cool.
! They shed their leaves in winters to protect themselv es from cold.
Plan ts that grow in desertsâ€” Some plan ts grow in hot and dry places with very 
poor rainfall. They are called xerophytes. Some examples of such plan ts are cactus, 
date palm, babool and keekar.
Environmental Studies-5 36

Exceptional features of Cactusâ€”
! The leaves of cactus are reduced to spines to prevent the loss of water by 
transpir ation.
! The stem of cactus is green, thick and flesh y which stores food and water. It 
releases this water when there is no rain.
! The green stem contains chlor ophyll and instead of leaves, the stem itself 
mak es food for the plan t.
Plan ts that grow in hot and humid regionsâ€” Some plan ts like teak, rubber , coffee, 
tea and coconut grow in hot and humid clima te.
Special featuresâ€”
! These trees do not shed their leaves and remain green throughout the year. 
That is why they are called evergreen trees. 
Plan ts that grow in marshy regionsâ€” Marshy 
places have clayey soil and plenty of water. 
Mangr ove trees grow in the marshy regions.
Special featuresâ€”
! The roots of these plan ts spread out deep under the ground in sear ch of 
water.
! They have small reduced leaves.
Environmental Studies-537

Special featuresâ€”
! In such water logged places, the soil does not allow the roots to breathe; so 
the roots grow above the soil and breathe through the tiny openings at their 
tips. Such roots are called breathing roots.
Aquatic Plants
There are three kinds of aquatic plantsâ€” free floating, fixed floating and 
under water plan ts.
Free Floa ting Plan tsâ€” Plan ts like duckw eed, water hyacinth and wolffia float freely 
on water.
Special featuresâ€”
! They have spongy bodies with lots of emp ty spaces filled with air.
! Leaves have thin waxy coating to prevent damag e from water.
! The stems are reduced.
! Roots are not well developed.
Fixed Floating Plantsâ€” Some 
plan ts like water lily and lotus have 
roots that fix the plan ts in the mud 
at the bottom of the pond.
Special featuresâ€”
! They have flat plate-like leaves coated with wax that prevents them from 
rotting.
! The stems are very flexible. They bend with the flow of water and thus do not 
get damag ed with strong water currents.

! The stems are hollo w and light that keeps the flowers and leaves floating on 
water.
! Stoma ta are presen t on the upper surface of the leaves for them to breathe 
easily .
Under water (submer ged) Plan tsâ€” 
Plan ts like hydrilla and tape grass 
grow comple tely under water.
Special featuresâ€”
! Their roots fix them in the muddy soil.
! Their leaves arise in clusters from the roots and do not have stoma ta.
! They breathe through the small air spaces on their body surface. 
Some Special Plants
Insectiv orous Plan tsâ€” Venus flytrap, Sunde w and the Pitcher plan t are examples 
of such plan ts. They have green leaves that mak e food for them. However, they 
grow in places wher e the soil is poor in nitrogen and other miner als needed by 
plan ts. To get these miner als, they trap insects for food. Hence, these plan ts are 
called insectiv orous plan ts.
Venus flytrap has leaves that are folded into two 
halves. The leaves have long hair like structur es 
on their edges. When an insect touches the hair, 
the leaf shuts, trapping the insect inside.
In  leaves are pitcher shaped pitcher plan ts,
with a lid. When an insect goes inside the 
pitcher , the lid closes and the insect is trapped.

Digestive SystemLet'sKnow Let'sKnow
The food we eat cannot be used by our body directly . It needs to be broken 
down into a simpler form. The process of breaking down of food into a simpler 
form that can be used by our body is called digestion. The organ system that 
help s in digestion of food is called digestive system.
The digestive system has man y organs that work together in digesting food. Let us 
see how food is digested through digestive system. 
Environmental Studies-5 44Unitâ€“II : The Living World

Excretion
The wastes which are produced inside the body of the living organisms need to be 
remo ved from time to time. If these wastes are not remo ved, they may become 
toxic or poisonous for the body . The process of remo ving the wastes from the body 
is called excretion.
The main excretory organs in humans areâ€“
! It excretes excess amoun t of water, salt Skinâ€“ 
and urea in the form of sweat.
! Carbon dioxide produced during Lungsâ€“ 
respir ation is excreted out through the lungs 
with the help of nose.! The digestion of the food starts in the 
mouth. When w e che w the f ood, saliv e 
in the mouth mixes with the food. This 
makes food softer and easier to 
swallow. Saliva also changes the 
insoluble starch presen t in the food into 
soluble sugars.
! The food then passes into the stomach 
through the food pipe. The stomach is a 
hollo w, muscular , bag like structur e.
! In the stomach, digestive juices 
(secr eted by stomach) get mixed with 
the food and further break down the 
food into smaller particles.
! From the stomach, the food passes into 
a long, coiled tube called the small 
intestine. Here, the food is mixed with more digestive juices. Some of these 
juices are produced in the small intestine and some are produced by the liver 
and pancr eas. These juices help to comple tely digest our food.
! The digested food is absorbed by the walls of the small intestine. Thus the 
process of digestion ends here and the undig ested food is passed into the 
large intestine and is thrown out from the body through the anus.Human Dig estive system
